This is a filament filter/lubricator i made for my ikea lack enclosure.
What you need:

  1. Three printed pieces
  2. ~58mm of 1.75mm PTFE tubing
  3. Any pen spring
  4. Cotten ball or whatever you will use as filter
  5. Miscellaneous Hardware

Instructions:

  1. Print three pieces
  2. Cut ~58mm piece of 1.75mm ptfe tubing
  3. Drill ~6-7mm diameter hole through lack
  4. Insert the ptfe tubing into the printed bottom filament filter passthrough piece and insert into drilled hole through the bottom of the lack roof (the ptfe tubing should now extend through the top of the lack)
  5. Insert screw to secure filament filter passthrough on bottom
  6. Place the Printed filament filter base on top of the lack and fit over remaining ptfe tubing
  7. Screw down filament filter base
  8. Use any pen spring and a long M3 screw to screw filament filter cover over the filament filter base
  9. Use a cotten ball or whatever you want as the filter inside the base

title: Extruder for a cheap chinese I3 Clone

description.text:
This is my Extruder Design for the Cheap Chinese I3 clone i bought from ebay. One of the things i didn't like on it, was the Extruder, where the counterbearing was fixed, so you couldn't adjust the preasure from the bearing to the transportationgear which often caused hopping/skipping on the filament. Since there wasn't enough space for the Extruder Designs i found here on thingiverse or i havent had a suitable spring laying around i simply designed this extruder. It uses the bearing from the stock extruder, 3x M3 x 10mm countersunk screws for the extruder arm, 2x M3 x 16mm cylinder head screws for mounting the extruder on the stepper motor, one long (20mm or longer) M3 screw and a nut for adjusting the pressure of the bearing against the filament and a few M3 washers.

The new design also has the possibility to mount a printing fan to cool your printed parts, which doesn't work perfectly but i had a 60mm fan laying around so that's why i designed it. ;-) https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2567897

Hi and thanks.
Just plain old hard work really. Everything is sanded then sprayed with primer filler, and sanded, and sprayed........you get the picture.
A base coat of silver followed by latex paint applied in high wear areas then sprayed with red oxide primer. Allow to dry and peel off the latex.
Finally sand with a very fine wet and dry to wear through the red oxide in places to give the worn away look.
A bit of black wash to finish is yet to be done on this model but will help pop out the details.

title: Traxxas TRX-4 Remote Undercarriage Power Switch

description.text:
Remix of Puredeath's original. There is NO changes to the mount. The design of that part is flawless, and works great.

Several changes/improvements to the rocker design:

1) The rocker has been extended and rounded off so that it can be actuated without a key. I know there are mixed opinions on this, but see the video, it's not protruding in an area that I can imagine anything other than a stick pointing straight out of the trail catching on, and it's reverse motion is limited by change #2.

2) Added a dimple and slope to the ESC side of the top portion of the rocker so that it cannot swing in the reverse direction more than ~1mm. This further reduces any possibility of the rocker getting down into a position where it could interfere with undercarriage clearance.

3) Adjusted the thickness of the rocker where it goes through the mount (made it slightly thicker) to reduce side-to-side motion. If it's snug after you print it, make sure you've trimmed off any jaggies at the edges that may have resulted from overhangs or supports.

4) Adjusted the thickness of the rocker where it goes between the body and slider (made it slightly thinner) for better clearance. On some trucks (like mine) the original was too tight here, as the sliders sat just slightly closer to the body.

Demo Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hXytwF1WSyU

Thanks for looking, and happy trailing!

As I began to print more on the MakerBot Replicator 2 I decided to spend an hour to design this filament reel holder (spool holder) for my MakerBot Replicator 3D printer. The whole project took about 3 hours to print and to complete the design.

In short:

  • Two bearings type 6000 were used to get smooth movement without friction. Bearings stay in two bearing holders. The bearing pocket's walls have small draft to get good snapping of the bearings inside the pockets.
    • For different filament reels different inserts were printed (in the project were attached the 51mm and 53mm diameter inserts, on request I could add more models - just let me know).
    • A screw M10x100 was used to hold the bearings and to tide the left/right inserts to the reel
    • The screw M10 was welded on 1.5mm sheet metal 36mm wide and bent to go inside the Replicator 2 reel holes. I was thinking to 3D print some holder around the screw but I found the welding was faster and easier for me to make the attachment.

The final result is - smooth and reliable reel holder without lots of efforts.

description.text: While demonstrating 3D printing, several people admired my Fairbanks Morse Hit and Miss Engine http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:113398/#files but asked if I had a model of a John Deere engine. Seems here in Minnesota there are quite a few John Deere collectors. Well, I figured that would be easy enough. Just place a water tank on top of the cylinder of the Fairbanks model. But then I did some research. The John Deere Type E engines were much smaller than the Fairbanks, and look very different from them. These Deere engines were sized from 1-1/2 to 6 horse power and there were lots of them. So I started this model from scratch. It is about 1/10 scale for the 1-1/2 hp engine. The skids were typically wood and the rest painted John Deere green. These small engines are still popular for powering ice cream makers. The fuel line running from the (gas tank) to the cylinder head is a piece of 1.75 mm filament. The holes may need some reaming to accommodate it.

description.text:
This first order ambisonic microphone enclosure can be used to create immersive sound. Many people have been introduced to VR but they are not aware that there is a branch of research dedicated to VR sound. Ambisonics is an old technology that has been resurfacing with the growth of VR.

After a lot of trials and error, my friend Yigal Kamel (who is brilliant btw) helped me make this enclosure which we are using as our first prototype. We also made some PCBs and soldered some circuits in order to get the whole thing to work. The audio was decoded using Omnitone. Check out the ForgeJS library for an easy to deploy FOA decoding solution.

The encoding is really easy (written in Matlab but you can use Octave too!):

W = FLU + FRD + BLD + BRU <---omni
X = FLU + FRD - BLD - BRU <---front/back
Y = FLU - FRD + BLD - BRU <---left/right
Z = FLU - FRD - BLD + BRU <---up/down

FLU = front left up
FRD = front right down
BLD = back left down
BRU = back right up

(the front of the mic, therefore, is between where there is one capsule pointing up and left and one pointing right and down)

The rest of this page will walk you through what you have to do in order to build one of your own!

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

1 mm

Notes:

I, unfortunately, am not an experience 3D printer. I was the team manager for this project. I basically had to know enough about PCB design, CAD design and programming to make sure that the mic worked, I am no expert in any of these things.

What I do know is that this is not the easiest CAD file to print, check out this for an easier print. The files are compiled using OpenSCAD. I believe you need to add the files to your path in order for the build to work, I haven't tried it yet.

I also know that if you want to use our mic enclosure you are going to need a pretty decent printer. Even with the nice printer we had to file the plastic a bit to fit out PCBs. Hope this can help someone! Luckily, you don't need to BUY the printer, there are online services that can send the files to for printing!

Check this one out!

Email me for help
We used some support, so the guys at NYU helped us clean it up. 🤩

Solely about the CAD design

We knew we need a tetrahedral object to begin. We found the angles of the faces online and created the tetrahedron accordingly. We also knew how large the inscribed circle need to be to fit the PCBs plus a little bit extra padding. We used those numbers to make the tetrahedron. From there we simply created the cylinders for the PCBs and made sure that we were accounting for the thickness of the wires. Each PCB need four cables. While the gauge of these wires is pretty thin, they add up. Our next version will have smaller PCBs. Our hope is that the new design will improve spatial aliasing problems.

This is in TinkerCad but we designed it in Solidworks The first version had walls that were too thin and didn't account for the thickness of the wires. 🤔

Unabridged tutorial As soon as you have everything you need to build the full mic we suggest you get everything together and lay it flat on a table. Categorize and organize all the elements of the build. Let there be nothing more and nothing less than what you need on said table. It helps!
  • Soldering gun: the hotter the better. If the gun is not hot enough it will be very hard to get the precision you need.
  • Hard solder for the breakout board: You will use this solder to connect the battery to the PCB and the cables from the mic to adaptors that fit into your soundcard. You can use any soundcard that has 4 inputs. Remember, keep phantom power off!
  • Solder paste for MEMS mics: You will use this solder paste to mount the capsules to the PCB in the reflow oven, if you don't have access to a reflow oven check this out. Essentially you put a bit of this stuff on the PCBs and use tweezers to lay the components on top. It's tricky but with a little bit of practice, we're sure you'll get it.

description.text:
Here is my take on a filament guide for extruders fitted to LulzBot Taz 4,5,6 printers, of course these may fit other extruders. I found somthing similar with an open clip type tube holder, but my tube kept falling out.

This guide bolts on using the same screw that holds the extruder head ion place, however, you will need a slightly longer bolt (approx 3 to 5mm longer) to fit this.

The guide has a lead in so the tube is easy to insert, then should bite towards the end and hold the tube in place. If it's too tight open it up a little using a 6.3mm / 1/4" drill bit. However, do this by hand otherwise you may go all the way through and remove the bottom tube stop! Of course this isn't an issue, you can open the holder straight through for a looser fit and have the filament guide poke out the bottom.

There are a couple of versions of this guide to fit the following LulzBot extruders:

  • Single Extruder V2 - "TAZ5 SEV2 Filament Guide.stl"
  • Single Extruder V2.1 - "TAZ6 SEV2_1 Filament Guide.stl" or "TAZ6 SEV2_1 Filament Guide V2"
  • FlexyStruder V2 - "TAZ5 SEV2 Filament Guide.stl"
  • MOAR Extruder - "MOAR Filament Guide V2.stl"

The "TAZ6 SEV2_1 Filament Guide V2" puts the filament guide directly over head rather than coming in at an angle. This makes extracting/installing filament easier than the "TAZ6 SEV2_1 Filament Guide" version.

description.text:
Non-magnetic, lightweight, replacement fan duct for the 40mm filament (part) cooling fan.

I was printing some items that I had to drop magnets into, but when the stock metal fan duct moved over the print, the magnets would fly up and attach to the fan duct. This plastic fan duct solved the problem.

Magnetic Construction Toys

I've designed this to print without supports. Simply snap off the built-in support for the duct opening when it's done printing.

Looks so much like the stock fan duct, all your friends will think it is.

The 45 degree scoop inside is to prevent overhangs and allow it to be printed without supports. It shouldn't negatively impact the airflow and also gives the screws some extra material to bite into.

The holes are threaded for the existing M3 screws. Screw in tightly, but don't over tighten.

This is a bowden attachement which was designed as a add-on to fit on any existing extruder and x-carriage of a Prusa Mendel.
As you can see in the picture, there is a mounting bracket for the extruder which mounts on the threaded rods at the top of the printer. The hotend mounting piece is meant to fit on any existing Prusa x-carriage. The bowden tube is held in place with a M4 nut threaded onto each end of the tube.
I used 2mm ID/4mm OD PTFE tube from seemecnc.com which seems to work.
This whole setup was tested and extrusion was achieved but it has yet to be tested extensively.

• Review the dimentions for the hotend attachement and generate a STL file which fits onto yours (the one here will probably not fit any existing hotend)
  • Print the top mounting piece in your favorite material
  • Print the hotend attachement in ABS since it is meant to take some heat.
  • Remove the obstructions (support material) from where the bowden tubes should be inserted in each objects
  • Insert the bowden tube in the extruder mount and thread an M4 nut on the tube, leaving a long enough length to reach the extruder's filament path.
  • Insert a M4 nut in the hotend mount and screw the bowden tube into it from the top.

I found that 22-24mm bolts worked well for me when adding this endstop trigger.

These hold downs slide into place and can be moved around at will. The extruder and fan duct remain clear as the machine goes through the Homing Cycle, Level Cycle and Start Cycle. The plastic fan duct only has about 1/16th of an inch clearance. Consider filing or sanding just the Tip of the Swing Arm Top to add more clearance. If you use a custom duct you will need to do some testing to make sure you have clearance.

Revisions: The Slide Brace part as been revised to allow for more clearance. As the PLA Slide Brace "Breaks-IN" / Bends / Warps it still works fine but a slight adjustment was necessary. Let me know if you ever print this and out of what material. PLA works fine but ABS may be a better choice. The old Slide Brace STL & STEP files were deleted and replaced with a new file name with R1 on the end of the name.

Possible Issues:
The heatbed may cause the PLA Slide Brace Part to become soft and bend too much. I use a 0.19 inch thick cork sheet on the bottom for insulation so the heat is blocked. ABS filament may be a better choice for the Slide Brace Part. I was too lazy to take off the cork just to test this. Please report your results.

It is very possible to run the extruder tip into the clamps. Warning / Disclaimer; You could damage your machine by running the extruder into the clamps. If you download this design you will agree that any damage caused while using these hold downs is completely your responsibility. I can’t think of all the ways you can run the extruder into these hold downs but I offer a few things to think about and feel free to add to the list. The extruder tip could hit the hold downs if you jog the machine into them or start the homing sequence with the extruder lined up (on either side) for a head on collision and etc. so care must be used but I think with a bit of thought everyone should be able to handle that. I suggest the first few times you run the automatic sequence for Start - Home or Level that you keep your finger on the On/Off switch in case you need to do a quick stop. The safest technique / habit is to always have the Z Axis height a few steps lower than the Home Position before activating any automatic sequences. (i.e.: Start – Level or Home)

Updates:
My clamp design failed on a tall vertical print. About 3 hours into the print the glass plate slipped.

Good News: After more testing, I determined that I simply needed to tighten the clamps down a bit more. I also smeared about a dozen glue stick marks on the bottom of the glass in hopes that this would act as a non skid surface. The plate removes from the bed without any indication of the glue stick so I really don't think the glue stick did anything. I still think 3 clamps is all that is needed but a 4th clamp would be even better I guess. I still like the idea of adding some sort of non skid to the blue build tac. If anyone has suggestions on this please add a comment. BTW: My Build Tac is very smooth and almost slick.

I have printed many parts now and this hold down design continues to work perfectly.

Printing Information: I used PLA at 100% Fill Density. ABS may be a better choice but the PLA does work for me.

Parts To Print: Note: The correct orientation to lay out the parts for printing are shown in the CAD photo where all the parts are laying on the glass bed. The individual STL photos are not all in the proper orientation for printing. Important It may look better to print the slide base in a different orientation but the part will loose strustural strength if you print it wrong.

Slide Base - Quantity of 3 – Use a small round file to clean out the hole. Note: This hole is designed to be a loose fit. The file named “Slide Base” is for Heatbeds with no insulation on the bottom. I request that you post a message and let everyone know if this Slide Base worked for you. I have insulation on my Bed so I did not test this standard Slide Base. I don’t know if the fit will be correct or if heat will cause issues.

Slide Base Modified – Shown in the CAD photos in Yellow. This file is named “Slide Base Modified” and is for those that use 0.19 inch thick cork to insulate the bottom of the heatbed. Use a small round file to clean out the hole. Note: This hole is designed to be a loose fit.

Swing Arm - Quantity of 3– After printing; screw a 6-32 Bolt down tight onto the Nut. Also; file or sand just the top tip to add a bit more clearance from the plastic fan duct.

Adjustment Wheel - Quantity of 6 – Consider using Loctite Super Glue Gel Control on the Wheel Nuts.

Fasteners: Bolt: #6-32 1 1/4inch & 3 Nuts - The 1 ¼ inch bolt length works for a glass thickness of 1/8 inch or less. If you use thicker glass you will probably need a 1 ½ inch length bolt.

Instructions for using the clamps:
These Hold Downs require a binding action to work. The CAD drawings show all parts in a perfect vertical alignment but in reality the Slide Base bolt hole is designed oversized so that the Swing Arm will tilt back allowing the required binding action. See the photo.
To set the clamp; push up from the bottom and swing the arm into position. Press down on the tip of the Swing Arm onto the glass and tighten the top adjustment wheel to a light pressure position now lock the top wheel in place by tightening the bottom wheel. Do not over tighten! The Slide Brace will start to bend if the adjustment wheels are over tightened. Important

Note: There will be a period of break-in because the PLA Slide Base part will bend a bit at the 90 degree point but then stablize.

Also; I do not use a shim to compensate for the extra height of the .125" glass thickness however I did notice that the AFT SCREW was not installed on the silver part that holds the Z Axis Screw in position. I intalled the scew from the extra parts that came with the machine and this screw head acts just like a shim would. Another user said he does not use a shim either but simply tightens the bed all the way down and then does a new Level sequence and adjust the bed which also worked for me.

Release the clamp by simply turning the Swing Arm off to the side. As the PLA settles it will become a bit bent under the bed and therefore you will need to readjust the clamps.

I have include both STEP and STL files. No tip is expected but I will accept them. Thanks!

If you decide to purchase glass and want a high quality type which may not be necessary. I recommend a company on eBay named go3dprint.https://www.ebay.com/usr/go3dprint I have no affiliation except that I am highly satisfied with my purchase and service after the sale.

description.text:
This is a simple model of a city water tower for model railroads. This design is based on pictures on the internet and does not model a specific water tower.  
The overall height of the water tower is 116 mm. According to Wikipedia, a typical water tower is 130 ft. Therefore, it is not possible to print a properly scaled water tower on a Makerbot Replicator 2 (not even for z scale). I printed one for visual effects for a N-scale layout.

Parts list: None. Assembly instructions: None. Printing instructions: Adhesion to the build plate is very important. The water tower is hollow so the infill percentage is not important. The water tower was printed on a Makerbor Replicator2
  • PLA (Makerbot filament)
  • Printed: Low(faster) resolution, 8% infill, 2 shells, 0.30 mm layer height, 230C
    • Some best practices for printing:
  • optimize print parameters for your printer, filament, etc (only you can determine the best parameters)
  • use good filament
  • level your build plate prior to printing complex parts. it's worth the few minutes it takes. always level after removing tape, or if pulling hard to remove a part.
  • make sure the build plate is clean.
  • if using blue tape, stretch it tight when applying it to the build plate.
  • if you have small holes in the blue tape, print the thing in a good section of the tape.
  • pre-feed the filament 30 to 60-s before printing (i.e., run load for 30-60s)
  • do not print several complicated parts in one build (do complex parts by themselves)
  • I find that printing faster is better (probably so the filament can't ball up in one spot)
  • make sure that there aren't any obstructions on the spool, such as some filament used to hold it in place during shipping
  • when the filament spool gets low, the filament can be tightly wound on the spool and the filament may not feed properly... take special care...
  • when a new spool is used, it is easy for the filament to jump outside the spool and then it will bind up later around the spool holder ruining your build
  • make sure it is easy for the filament to enter the filament feed tube. others have designed spools, mounts, etc. for that purpose. i use a small rope that forces the filament away from the spool before entering the filament feed tube.
  • if you hear clicking when printing, that may be a result of the filament wrapped around the spool and not feeding
  • for the replicaor2, look at the blob a filament in the left front part of the build plate and then the trail of filament to the biuild location. there should be a glob, and the line of filament should be continuous and smooth
  • one way to remove parts when using blue tape is to use a very thin spatula bought in craft-art stores (advice from youtube). get one with a wide, blunt front end (not long and thin). mine is 11 mils thick (0.011") and 20-mm wide at the front. a painting spatula/scraper in hardware stores won't work and may damage the build plate. (I use blue tape so I don't have any best practices for bare plates, heated plates or for other tapes like mylar)
  • perform regular maintenance (grease, etc).
  • when I continued to have problems printing even after performing maintenance, following troublshooting instructions, changing filaments, cleaning gears, cleaning everything, optimizing print parameters, changing temperatures, etc., I bought a new extruder assembly from Makerbot and it solved all of my problems.

description.text: Resin vats are expensive. So is FEP sheet. Resin vat screws are fragile. I found this out the hard way! Decided to create my own "disposable" resin vat that needs no screws, only ABS or "Raptor" PLA from MakerGeeks (http://bit.ly/2xS5wh3), and some clear teflon (FEP) sheet (http://bit.ly/2xZe3y4), and a strong silicone sealant (I use Gorilla brand). Use a filament that is strong, that's why I recommend ABS or Raptor PLA, which can be annealed in the oven and actually becomes strong and more heat/chemical resistant than ABS or carbon filament! Anyway, using a flattened or smoothed bead of silicon sealant all the way around the bottom will adhere the teflon sheet to the frame, and then a bead around the inside will seal the build, and the pressure from the large vat screws on the printer combine to make this thing leak-free. Do the same for the window, though I didn't add an extra bead, and window does not leak either. I have removed this and put it back on several times and still no leaks. I do recommend placing something heavy on the frame to press down on the join between the frame and the teflon sheet while it sets to aid in adhesion. I allowed it all to cure for about 12 hours, even though the sealant says 30 minutes.

ANNEAL THE RAPTOR AND AN ABS CAVEAT!

If you use the Raptor PLA, make sure you anneal the parts in the oven following these instructions!

  1. Place piece on glass or ceramic or stone

  2. Place a ceramic tile (or glass) over the piece to help prevent warping (if piece is flat on top)

  3. Place item in a cold oven

  4. Heat oven to 212F/100C

  5. Set timer for 15 minutes

  6. After 15 minutes, turn oven off - leave oven closed, leave piece in oven

  7. Set timer for 45 minutes

  8. After 45 minutes, remove ceramic or glass tile from the top of piece

  9. Remove piece from oven (it should be pretty cool but not cold)
    Item is still somewhat soft, so don’t drop it

  10. Let item cool completely (maybe another 30 minutes)

Item is ready for use!

description.text:
Do you have an Espresso machine? Does the coffee honestly knock cleanly out? Does your Portafilter have 2 inserts that fall out when you knock it?

Personally, my coffee machines have never been good at drying the coffee out enough to knock out a puck, and when I try, my Gaggia Portafilter, designed to have a one or two cup insert, often comes apart.

So what have I done all these years?

I've used plastic spoons, backs of spoons, fork handles or whatever I can get my hands on to scrape the grinds out. At home we have made our way through many a plastic spork. At work every plastic spoon is stolen by cleaners, every metal one is taken by colleagues.

So now I have a solution, an OFFICIAL Grind Extraction Device, Or G.E.D. for short. You can tell its official because it says so on the handle, so no one will throw it away or take it to stir their tea.

'But its just a spoon!?' I hear you say - No it isn't, and here is why....

The Official GED has been designed to fit a 58mm Portafilter with precision. The tool end is designed to fit the curve exactly, leading to a 500%* increase in coffee removal efficiency. The gentle curved edges and thick handle give it a premium feel of quality and assist in applying the pressure needed to extract a well compacted puck. And also, It says 'Official G.E.D' on the handle - which proves its not a spoon.

The Official G.E.D is available in two versions. One with a horizontal tool end, and one who's tool end is at a slight angle. My preference is for the angled tool end as it gives a more rounded backside, but the horizontal version requires less supports.

Enjoy your coffee, impress your friends and loved ones, use an Official G.E.D

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1-0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Photographed versions were printed in light grey at 0.1mm to illustrate the GED, but this device is best printed in black, because black coffee is cool.

0.2mm layers are functionally fine if you want a quick print.

Print flat, so the writing is face up.

Line supports seem to be best if using the same material for supports. Support density of 8% or over is needed - preview the curves around the tool end before printing to ensure you have enough coverage at curve points. You will probably need to snip and sand a little at the back.

*500% increase in efficiency is an estimate - but it honestly does make a noticeable difference
